<h1>Triple Surface Aircraft</h1>
<p>Triple surface aircraft are rare due to the complex aerodynamics but some
do exist and are even in use today. Some examples of three surface aircraft are:</p>
<ul>
	<li><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curtiss_No._1">Curtiss-Herring No. 1 Reims Racer</a> - 1908</li>
	<li><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/De_Havilland_Biplane_No._1">De Havilland, Bi-plane No. 1</a> - 1909</li>
	<li><a href="http://www.luft46.com/bv/bvp192.html">Blohm und Voss BV P192</a> - 1942</li>
	<li><a href="http://www.airventuremuseum.org/collection/aircraft/Rutan%20Grizzly%2072.asp">Rutan Grizzly</a> - 1982</li>
	<li><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grumman_X-29">Grumman X-29</a> - 1986</li>
	<li><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Piaggio_P-180">Piaggio P-180 Avanti</a> - 1986</li>
	<li><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scaled_Composites_Catbird">Scaled Composites Model 81 Catbird</a> - 1988</li>
</ul>

<h2>Advantages</h2>
<ul>
	<li>Higher lift curve slope</li>
	<li>Pitch down during stall</li>
</ul>

<h2>Disadvantages</h2>
<ul>
	<li>Additional skin friction</li>
	<li>Possible higher aircraft weight</li>
	<li>Unique stability characteristics</li>
	<li>Unique aeroelastic characteristics</li>
</ul>

